│ output. The first transformation point is within                              │
│ preparePlanForEpilogueVectorLoop, specifically where it tries to find         │
│ EPResumeVal by scanning preheader PHIs. The stack indicates this is during    │
│ LoopVectorizePass::processLoop -> runImpl. No other transformations are       │
│ logged before the failure, consistent with the assertion being in the first   │
│ modification stage when preparing the VPlan for the epilogue vector           │
│ loop.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe code assumes that a resume PHI for the  │
│ canonical IV has been created during earlier vectorization planning of the    │
│ main vector loop and is available in the loop preheader. It looks for a PHI   │
│ with incoming VectorTripCount from 'MainMiddle' and zero from the iteration   │
│ count check block. In edge cases (e.g., loops with trip count 0,              │
│ degenerate/infinite structure, or when the main vector loop is not formed),   │
│ such a PHI may not exist. The function even has a FIXME: \"Improve modeling   │
│ for canonical IV start values in the epilogue loop.\" This indicates          │
│ awareness that the current modeling is incomplete. When the main vector loop  │
│ doesn't execute (e.g., vector TC == 0), the canonical IV start for the        │
│ epilogue should be zero, but the code doesn't handle the absence of the       │
│ resume PHI and asserts instead.\n\nGiven the reproducer and the name hint,    │
│ vector trip count could be 0, and the search for the resume PHI fails,        │
│ leaving EPResumeVal null. The assertion thus fires. The correct behavior in   │
│ this case is to treat the epilogue's canonical IV start as zero when the main │
│ vector loop didn't run or couldn't provide a resume value.\n\n4. Proposed     │
│ Edit Point(s):\n- File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp,      │
│ lines 10407-10412.\n  Replace the hard assertion on EPResumeVal with a robust │
│ fallback: if EPResumeVal is not found, synthesize a zero constant of the      │
│ canonical IV type and use it as the start value for the epilogue's canonical  │
│ IV. This aligns with the intended semantics when the main loop doesn't        │
│ execute (incoming from the iteration count check is zero) and with the FIXME  │
│ comment about modeling start values.\n\n  Concretely:\n  - Remove             │
│ `assert(EPResumeVal && \"must have a resume value for the canonical IV\");`\n │
│ - Set VPV to Plan.getOrAddLiveIn(EPResumeVal) if present; otherwise set VPV   │
│ to Plan.getOrAddLiveIn(ConstantInt::get(IdxTy, 0)).\n  - Keep the subsequent  │
│ usage checks and setting of IV's operand.\n\n  The edited code will look      │
│ like:\n  \n  PHINode *EPResumeVal = ...; // existing search\n  VPValue        │
│ *VPV;\n  if (EPResumeVal)\n    VPV = Plan.getOrAddLiveIn(EPResumeVal);\n      │
│ else\n    VPV = Plan.getOrAddLiveIn(ConstantInt::get(IdxTy, 0));\n  // keep   │
│ the following assert on uses and IV->setOperand(0, VPV);\n\n  This change     │
│ ensures that even if the resume PHI is missing, the epilogue vector loop can  │
│ be prepared with a safe start value (zero), matching the expected semantics   │
│ when the main loop does not contribute a resume value.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe │
│ crash results from an overstrict assertion that assumes a resume PHI must     │
│ exist for the canonical IV. In cases where the main vector loop does not      │
│ produce such a PHI (e.g., vector trip count is zero or due to degenerate loop │
│ structure), the pass should fall back to a sensible default. By replacing the │
│ assertion with a fallback to a zero constant of the canonical IV type, we     │
